{"title_page": "Sherri Tenpenny", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n'''Sherri Tenpenny''' is an American [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|osteopathic physician]] and anti-vaccination activist from [[Ohio]] who supports the discredited [[Vaccines and autism|theory that vaccines cause autism]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.smh.com.au/comment/smh-editorial/antivaccination-views-are-misguided--but-not-illegal-20150110-12kk2c.html | title=Anti-vaccination views are misguided - but not illegal | work=Sydney Morning-Herald | date=11 January 2015 | accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> She is the author of four books opposing vaccination, and her 2015 lecture tour of Australia was cancelled due to a public outcry over her views on vaccination, which go against the established scientific consensus. She has no advanced clinical or research specialization in [[immunology]], [[vaccinology]], or [[public health]], nor has she ever published peer-reviewed research in any area related to vaccines or immunology.  Though due to her many years working as a director of an emergency department, as well as her extensive education as not only an osteopath and a physician, she does possess the knowledge to read and understand the peer reviewed mainstream medical journals to come to her conclusions.\n\n==Education and career==\nTenpenny graduated with a Bachelor of Arts from the [[University of Toledo]] in 1980, and subsequently received a [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] degree from the [[Kirksville College of Osteopathic Medicine]] in [[Missouri]] in  1984.<ref name=CV>{{cite web|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|title=Sherri J. Tenpenny, DO, AOBNMM (CV)|url=http://drtenpenny.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/SHERRI-CV-11-10-no-subtitles-no-dates.pdf|accessdate=9 February 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WCaxWL8A?url=http://drtenpenny.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/SHERRI-CV-11-10-no-subtitles-no-dates.pdf|archivedate=9 February 2015|format=PDF|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1986 to 1998, Tenpenny was the director of the emergency department at Blanchard Valley Hospital in [[Findlay, Ohio]]. She opened an osteopathic practice in 1994, and went on to establish two more such practices, in 1996 and 2011.<ref name=abc>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-01-07/who-is-anti-vaccination-campaigner-sherri-tenpenny/6004490 | title=Sherri Tenpenny: Who is the controversial anti-vaccination campaigner planning to visit Australia? | work=ABC News | date=7 January 2015 | accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nTenpenny had scheduled a speaking tour in Australia to occur starting in February 2015, but after objections were raised to her anti-vaccination views, all the venues at which she was scheduled to speak cancelled the talks in January, and the tour was called off.<ref name=bt-cancel>{{cite news |last1=Medew|first1=Julia |title=US anti-vaccination campaigner Dr Sherri Tenpenny cancels tour of Australia |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/health/us-antivaccination-campaigner-dr-sherri-tenpenny-cancels-tour-of-australia-20150128-130qa4.html |accessdate=2 February 2015 |work=The Brisbane Times |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/jan/08/sydney-venue-cancels-seminar-us-anti-vaccine-activist-sherri-tenpenny | title=Sydney venue cancels seminar by US anti-vaccine activist Sherri Tenpenny | work=The Guardian | date=8 January 2015 | accessdate=12 January 2015 | author=Milman, Oliver}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri J.|author-mask=0|title=Saying No to Vaccines: A Resource Guide for All Ages |date=2008 |publisher=NMA Media Press |location= Middleburg Heights, Ohio |isbn=978-0-97909-104-9}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|author-mask=0|title=FOWL! Bird Flu: It's Not What You Think |date=2006 |publisher=Insight Pub. Co.|location=Sevierville, Tenn. | isbn=978-1-93286-387-1}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|author-mask=0|title=The Risks, the Benefits, the Choices, a Resource Guide for Parents |date=2006 |publisher=Insight Publishing |location=Sevierville, Tenn.  |isbn=978-0-97434-482-9}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|author-mask=0|title=A Healthier You!|date=2005|publisher=Insight Publishing|location=Sevierville, Tenn.|isbn=978-1-93286-385-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/healthieryou0000tenp}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://tenpennyimc.com/ Tenpenny IMC website]\n* [http://tenpennyimc.com/2011/05/09/dr-sherri-tenpenny-truthsquad-interview-on-vaccines-big-pharma-autism/ Tenpenny interview on vaccines and autism]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tenpenny, Sherri}}\n[[Category:American osteopathic physicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:University of Toledo alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women physicians]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American medical writers]]\n[[Category:Women medical writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n'''Sherri Tenpenny''' is an American [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|osteopathic physician]] and anti-vaccination activist from [[Ohio]] who supports the discredited [[Vaccines and autism|theory that vaccines cause autism]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.smh.com.au/comment/smh-editorial/antivaccination-views-are-misguided--but-not-illegal-20150110-12kk2c.html | title=Anti-vaccination views are misguided - but not illegal | work=Sydney Morning-Herald | date=11 January 2015 | accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> She is the author of four books opposing vaccination, and her 2015 lecture tour of Australia was cancelled due to a public outcry over her views on vaccination, which go against the established scientific consensus. She has no advanced clinical or research specialization in [[immunology]], [[vaccinology]], or [[public health]], nor has she ever published peer-reviewed research in any area related to vaccines or immunology.\n\n==Education and career==\nTenpenny graduated with a Bachelor of Arts from the [[University of Toledo]] in 1980, and subsequently received a [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] degree from the [[Kirksville College of Osteopathic Medicine]] in [[Missouri]] in  1984.<ref name=CV>{{cite web|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|title=Sherri J. Tenpenny, DO, AOBNMM (CV)|url=http://drtenpenny.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/SHERRI-CV-11-10-no-subtitles-no-dates.pdf|accessdate=9 February 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WCaxWL8A?url=http://drtenpenny.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/SHERRI-CV-11-10-no-subtitles-no-dates.pdf|archivedate=9 February 2015|format=PDF|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1986 to 1998, Tenpenny was the director of the emergency department at Blanchard Valley Hospital in [[Findlay, Ohio]]. She opened an osteopathic practice in 1994, and went on to establish two more such practices, in 1996 and 2011.<ref name=abc>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-01-07/who-is-anti-vaccination-campaigner-sherri-tenpenny/6004490 | title=Sherri Tenpenny: Who is the controversial anti-vaccination campaigner planning to visit Australia? | work=ABC News | date=7 January 2015 | accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nTenpenny had scheduled a speaking tour in Australia to occur starting in February 2015, but after objections were raised to her anti-vaccination views, all the venues at which she was scheduled to speak cancelled the talks in January, and the tour was called off.<ref name=bt-cancel>{{cite news |last1=Medew|first1=Julia |title=US anti-vaccination campaigner Dr Sherri Tenpenny cancels tour of Australia |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/health/us-antivaccination-campaigner-dr-sherri-tenpenny-cancels-tour-of-australia-20150128-130qa4.html |accessdate=2 February 2015 |work=The Brisbane Times |publisher=Fairfax Media |date=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/jan/08/sydney-venue-cancels-seminar-us-anti-vaccine-activist-sherri-tenpenny | title=Sydney venue cancels seminar by US anti-vaccine activist Sherri Tenpenny | work=The Guardian | date=8 January 2015 | accessdate=12 January 2015 | author=Milman, Oliver}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri J.|author-mask=0|title=Saying No to Vaccines: A Resource Guide for All Ages |date=2008 |publisher=NMA Media Press |location= Middleburg Heights, Ohio |isbn=978-0-97909-104-9}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|author-mask=0|title=FOWL! Bird Flu: It's Not What You Think |date=2006 |publisher=Insight Pub. Co.|location=Sevierville, Tenn. | isbn=978-1-93286-387-1}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|author-mask=0|title=The Risks, the Benefits, the Choices, a Resource Guide for Parents |date=2006 |publisher=Insight Publishing |location=Sevierville, Tenn.  |isbn=978-0-97434-482-9}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Tenpenny|first1=Sherri|author-mask=0|title=A Healthier You!|date=2005|publisher=Insight Publishing|location=Sevierville, Tenn.|isbn=978-1-93286-385-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/healthieryou0000tenp}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://tenpennyimc.com/ Tenpenny IMC website]\n* [http://tenpennyimc.com/2011/05/09/dr-sherri-tenpenny-truthsquad-interview-on-vaccines-big-pharma-autism/ Tenpenny interview on vaccines and autism]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tenpenny, Sherri}}\n[[Category:American osteopathic physicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:University of Toledo alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women physicians]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American medical writers]]\n[[Category:Women medical writers]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:29df:dc4d:955b:714:e952:c1e6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherri_Tenpenny"}
{"title_page": "Who's Gonna Save Us?", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| cover      = Wgsu.gif\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Living End]]\n| album      = [[Modern ARTillery]]\n| released   = 28 October, 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Whos-Gonna-Save-Us/dp/B00122E4UC|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2020-04-17|title=Who's Gonna Save Us - The Living End}}</ref>\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 03:21<ref>https://music.apple.com/lu/album/whos-gonna-save-us-single/5132550?l=de</ref>\n| label      = [[EMI]]\n| writer     = [[Chris Cheney]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[One Said To The Other]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n\"'''Who's Gonna Save Us?'''\" is a song by Australian [[punk rock]] band [[The Living End]]. It was released in October 2003, as the first [[Single (music)|single]] (not including ''One Said to the Other'' as it was re-recorded for the album) from the band's third album, ''[[Modern Artillery|Modern ARTillery]]''. \n\nIt reached number 37 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] and also charted in the United States, peaking at number 26 on the [[Alternative Songs|Hot Modern Rock Tracks]]. The song appeared in the television commercial and soundtrack for [[Michael Moore]]'s 2004 documentary film, ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = \n| title1          = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| length1         = 3:21\n\n| title2          = No Return\n| note2   = Demo\n| length2         =\n\n| title3          = The Avenue\n| length3         =\n| note3 = Demo\n\n| title4          = Just Too Bad\n| length4         = \n| note4 = Demo\n}}\n\n<small>Recorded and engineered by Lindsay Gravina at [[Sing Sing Studios]], [[Melbourne]]. Mixed by [[Jerry Finn]] at The Mastering Lab, [[Los Angeles]].</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Living End}}\n\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:The Living End songs]]\n[[Category:EMI Records singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Chris Cheney]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| cover      = Wgsu.gif\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Living End]]\n| album      = [[Modern ARTillery]]\n| released   = 28 October, 2003\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 03:21<ref>https://music.apple.com/lu/album/whos-gonna-save-us-single/5132550?l=de</ref>\n| label      = [[EMI]]\n| writer     = [[Chris Cheney]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[One Said To The Other]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n\"'''Who's Gonna Save Us?'''\" is a song by Australian [[punk rock]] band [[The Living End]]. It was released in October 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Whos-Gonna-Save-Us/dp/B00122E4UC|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2020-04-17|title=Who's Gonna Save Us - The Living End}}</ref>, as the first [[Single (music)|single]] (not including ''One Said to the Other'' as it was re-recorded for the album) from the band's third album, ''[[Modern Artillery|Modern ARTillery]]''. \n\nIt reached number 37 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] and also charted in the United States, peaking at number 26 on the [[Alternative Songs|Hot Modern Rock Tracks]]. The song appeared in the television commercial and soundtrack for [[Michael Moore]]'s 2004 documentary film, ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = \n| title1          = Who's Gonna Save Us?\n| length1         = 3:21\n\n| title2          = No Return\n| note2   = Demo\n| length2         =\n\n| title3          = The Avenue\n| length3         =\n| note3 = Demo\n\n| title4          = Just Too Bad\n| length4         = \n| note4 = Demo\n}}\n\n<small>Recorded and engineered by Lindsay Gravina at [[Sing Sing Studios]], [[Melbourne]]. Mixed by [[Jerry Finn]] at The Mastering Lab, [[Los Angeles]].</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Living End}}\n\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:The Living End songs]]\n[[Category:EMI Records singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Chris Cheney]]\n", "name_user": "Machr123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who%27s_Gonna_Save_Us%3F"}
{"title_page": "Bonham Boosters", "text_new": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name             = Bonham Boosters\n|allyears         = 1911\u20131914, 1921\u20131922\n|city             = Bonham, Texas\n|misc             =\n|logo             = \n|uniformlogo      = \n|class level      =  \n|past class level = {{plainlist|\n*Class D (1911\u20131914, 1921\u20131922)\n}}\n|current league   = \n|conference       =\n|division         = \n|past league      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Southwestern League]] (1898)\n*[[Texas-Oklahoma League]] (1911\u20131914)\n*Texas-Oklahoma League (1921\u20131922)\n}}\n|majorleague      = \n|pastmajorleague  = {{plainlist|\n*None\n}}\n|nickname         = \n|pastnames        = {{plainlist| \n*Bonham (1898)\n*'''Bonham Boosters''' (1911)\n*Bonham Tigers (1912)\n*Bonham Blues (1913)\n*Bonham Sliders (1914)\n*Bonham Favorites (1921)\n*Bonham Bingers (1922)\n}}\n|ballpark         = \n|pastparks        ={{plainlist|\n* Catron Park\n* Simpson Park\n}}\n|leaguechamps     =  None\n|divisionchamps   = \n|owner            = \n|manager          =\n|gm               =\n}}\nThe '''Bonham Boosters''' was the first moniker of the [[minor league baseball]] teams based in [[Bonham, Texas]]. Bonham played as members of the [[Texas-Oklahoma League]] (1911\u20131914, 1921\u20131922) and the [[Southwestern League]] (1898). Bonham teams featured a different moniker each season.\n\n[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] member [[Kid Nichols]] managed the 1914 Bonham Sliders.\n\n==History==\nProfessional baseball began in Bonham, when the city hosted a team in the 1898 Independent [[Southwestern League]]. Bonham finished 6\u20139 in 1898. The Southwestern season ran from April 21, 1898 to May 23, 1898.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SWL2/y-1898|title=1898 Southwestern League (SL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bb10507/y-1898|title=1898 Bonham Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi|title=Bonham, Texas Encyclopedia|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nBonham became members of the [[Texas-Oklahoma League]], playing in all six seasons of the league from 1911\u20131914 and 1921\u20131922, .<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Texas-Oklahoma_League|title=Texas-Oklahoma League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/league.cgi?code=TXOK&class=D|title=Texas-Oklahoma League (D) Encyclopedia and History|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe '''Bonham Boosters''' began play in the Class D [[Texas-Oklahoma League]] in 1911. The Boosters finished 54\u201360 4th in the league under Manager [[Jimmie Humphries]]. The Booster finished with the Altus Chiefs (31\u201344), [[Ardmore Blues]] (49\u201358), [[Cleburne Railroaders]] (61\u201350), Durant Educators (65\u201346), Gainesville Blue Ribbons, [[Lawton Medicine Men]] (17\u201331) and [[Wichita Falls Irish Lads]] (65\u201338) in the 1911 league standings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Boosters|title=Bonham Boosters - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1911|title=1911 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bb10510/y-1911|title=1911 Bonham Boosters Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>https://texasalmanac.com/sites/default/files/images/almanac-feature/Minor_League_in_Texas-TxAlm0809.pdf</ref>\n\nThe 1912 '''Bonham Tigers''' finished  53\u201335, 2nd in the Texas-Oklahoma League under Manager [[Roy Leslie]]. The league playoffs did not include Bonham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1912|title=1912 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bt10513/y-1912|title=1912 Bonham Tigers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Tigers|title=Bonham Tigers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1913, the'''Bonham Blues''' finished 5th in the Texas-Oklahoma League with a 56\u201368 record. The Blues' Manager was again Roy Leslie. On opening day On April 15, 1913, the Bonham Blues opened their new baseball park, playing  against the Texarkana Tigers. Bonham won the opener 3\u20130. Before the game, fans gathered at the square for a photo and a parade to the ballpark. The Bonham Daily Favorite on April 16, 1913 reported that \"Practically every business house in the city closed during the game which began at 3:15 o'clock, and perhaps the largest crowd that ever attended a ball game in Bonham was present. The grandstand and bleachers were full, and the crowd overflowed into right field.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1913|title=1913 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-bb10509|title=Bonham Blues Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Blues|title=Bonham Blues - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto3\">https://www.fannincountyhistory.org/baseball-1913.html</ref>\n\nBonham continued play as members of the Texas-Oklahoma League, the 1914 . The'''Bonham Sliders''' had a 47\u201358 record under managers Senter Reiney and [[Kid Nichols]] when the franchise disbanded on June 30, 1914. Nichols is a member of the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]]. The Texas-Oklahoma League folded entirely after the 1914 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Sliders|title=Bonham Sliders - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1914|title=1914 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bf10511/y-1914|title=Sports Statistics from the Stats Crew|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1921, the '''Bonham Favorites''' joined the reformed [[Texas-Oklahoma League]]. The Favorites finished 57\u201371 under Managers G. D. Pittman and Virgil Moss. Bonham finished 3rd in the league, joining the [[Ardmore Peps]] (87\u201340), Cleburne Generals (51\u201375), Graham Hijackers/[[Mineral Wells Resorters]] (49\u201379), [[Paris Snappers]] and [[Sherman Lions]] (48\u201378) in the 1921 league standings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bf10511/y-1921|title=1921 Bonham Favorites Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1921|title=1921 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Favorites|title=Bonham Favorites - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n1922 was the final year for the Texas-Oklahoma League and the Bonham franchise. The 1922 '''Bonham Bingers''' finished 39\u201353, 7th in the league. The Bingers' Manager was Les Tullos. Bonham was dropped from the league on July 22 when Cleburne disbanded. The 1922 Texas-Oklahoma League season ended on August 6, 1922, with National Association permission, due to a railroad strike. The league did not reform in 1923 and permanently disbanded. Bonham has not hosted another minor league team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1922|title=1922 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bb10508/y-1922|title=1922 Bonham Bingers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Bingers|title=Bonham Bingers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==The ballparks==\nBohnam teams likely played at '''Catron Park''' and '''Simpson Park'''. Both parks still exist today as public recreational parks. Catron Park is located at the 400 block of East 3rd Street, Bonham Texas, 75418.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-292|title=Unknown in Bonham, TX history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://visitbonham.com/event/art-in-the-park-simpson-park/|title=Art in the Park @ Simpson Park}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americantowns.com/venue/catron-park-bonham-tx.html|title=Catron Park|website=www.americantowns.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cityofbonham.org/parks-and-recreation.html|title=Parks and Recreation|website=CITY OF BONHAM}}</ref>\n\nBonham built a new ballpark for the 1913 season. The name of the 1913 new ballpark is unknown.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n===[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] alumni===\n*[[Kid Nichols]] (1914, MGR) Inducted, 1949\n===Notable alumni===\n*[[Ted Blankenship]] (1921\u20131922)\n*[[Buster Chatham]] (1922)\n*[[Jim Haislip]] (1911)\n*[[Jimmie Humphries]] (1911, MGR)\n*[[Roy Leslie]] (1912\u20131913, MGR)\n*[[George Milstead]] (1921\u20131922)\n*[[Reb Russell]] (1912)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham,_TX Baseball reference]\n[[Category:Fannin County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct baseball teams in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name             = Bonham Boosters\n|allyears         = 1911\u20131914, 1921\u20131922\n|city             = Bonham, Texas\n|misc             =\n|logo             = \n|uniformlogo      = \n|class level      =  \n|past class level = {{plainlist|\n*Class D (1911\u20131914, 1921\u20131922)\n}}\n|current league   = \n|conference       =\n|division         = \n|past league      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Southwestern League]] (1898)\n*[[Texas-Oklahoma League]] (1911\u20131914)\n*Texas-Oklahoma League (1921\u20131922)\n}}\n|majorleague      = \n|pastmajorleague  = {{plainlist|\n*None\n}}\n|nickname         = \n|pastnames        = {{plainlist| \n*Bonham (1898)\n*'''Bonham Boosters''' (1911)\n*Bonham Tigers (1912)\n*Bonham Blues (1913)\n*Bonham Sliders (1914)\n*Bonham Favorites (1921)\n*Bonham Bingers (1922)\n}}\n|ballpark         = \n|pastparks        ={{plainlist|\n* Catron Park\n* Simpson Park\n}}\n|leaguechamps     =  None\n|divisionchamps   = \n|owner            = \n|manager          =\n|gm               =\n}}\nThe '''Bonham Boosters''' was the first moniker of the [[minor league baseball]] teams based in [[Bonham, Texas]]. Bonham played as members of the [[Texas-Oklahoma League]] (1911\u20131914, 1921\u20131922) and the [[Southwestern League]] (1898). Bonham teams featured a different moniker each season.\n\n==History==\nProfessional baseball began in Bonham, when the city hosted a team in the 1898 Independent [[Southwestern League]]. Bonham finished 6\u20139 in 1898. The Southwestern season ran from April 21, 1898 to May 23, 1898.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SWL2/y-1898|title=1898 Southwestern League (SL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bb10507/y-1898|title=1898 Bonham Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi|title=Bonham, Texas Encyclopedia|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nBonham became members of the [[Texas-Oklahoma League]], playing in all six seasons of the league from 1911\u20131914 and 1921\u20131922, .<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Texas-Oklahoma_League|title=Texas-Oklahoma League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/league.cgi?code=TXOK&class=D|title=Texas-Oklahoma League (D) Encyclopedia and History|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe '''Bonham Boosters''' began play in the Class D [[Texas-Oklahoma League]] in 1911. The Boosters finished 54\u201360 4th in the league under Manager [[Jimmie Humphries]]. The Booster finished with the Altus Chiefs (31\u201344), [[Ardmore Blues]] (49\u201358), [[Cleburne Railroaders]] (61\u201350), Durant Educators (65\u201346), Gainesville Blue Ribbons, [[Lawton Medicine Men]] (17\u201331) and [[Wichita Falls Irish Lads]] (65\u201338) in the 1911 league standings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Boosters|title=Bonham Boosters - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1911|title=1911 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bb10510/y-1911|title=1911 Bonham Boosters Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>https://texasalmanac.com/sites/default/files/images/almanac-feature/Minor_League_in_Texas-TxAlm0809.pdf</ref>\n\nThe 1912 '''Bonham Tigers''' finished  53\u201335, 2nd in the Texas-Oklahoma League under Manager [[Roy Leslie]]. The league playoffs did not include Bonham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1912|title=1912 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bt10513/y-1912|title=1912 Bonham Tigers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Tigers|title=Bonham Tigers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1913, the'''Bonham Blues''' finished 5th in the Texas-Oklahoma League with a 56\u201368 record. The Blues' Manager was again Roy Leslie. On opening day On April 15, 1913, the Bonham Blues opened their new baseball park, playing  against the [[Texarkana Tigers]]. Bonham won the opener 3\u20130. Before the game, fans gathered at the square for a photo and a parade to the ballpark. The Bonham Daily Favorite on April 16, 1913 reported that \"Practically every business house in the city closed during the game which began at 3:15 o'clock, and perhaps the largest crowd that ever attended a ball game in Bonham was present. The grandstand and bleachers were full, and the crowd overflowed into right field.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1913|title=1913 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-bb10509|title=Bonham Blues Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Blues|title=Bonham Blues - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto3\">https://www.fannincountyhistory.org/baseball-1913.html</ref>\n\nBonham continued play as members of the Texas-Oklahoma League, the 1914 . The'''Bonham Sliders''' had a 47\u201358 record under managers Senter Reiney and [[Kid Nichols]] when the franchise disbanded on June 30, 1914. The Texas-Oklahoma League folded entirely after the 1914 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Sliders|title=Bonham Sliders - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1914|title=1914 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bf10511/y-1914|title=Sports Statistics from the Stats Crew|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1921, the '''Bonham Favorites''' joined the reformed [[Texas-Oklahoma League]]. The Favorites finished 57\u201371 under Managers G. D. Pittman and Virgil Moss. Bonham finished 3rd in the league, joining the [[Ardmore Peps]] (87\u201340), Cleburne Generals (51\u201375), Graham Hijackers/[[Mineral Wells Resorters]] (49\u201379), [[Paris Snappers]] and [[Sherman Lions]] (48\u201378) in the 1921 league standings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bf10511/y-1921|title=1921 Bonham Favorites Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1921|title=1921 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Favorites|title=Bonham Favorites - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n1922 was the final year for the Texas-Oklahoma League and the Bonham franchise. The 1922 '''Bonham Bingers''' finished 39\u201353, 7th in the league. The Bingers' Manager was Les Tullos. Bonham was dropped from the league on July 22 when Cleburne disbanded. The 1922 Texas-Oklahoma League season ended on August 6, 1922, with National Association permission, due to a railroad strike. The league did not reform in 1923 and permanently disbanded. Bonham has not hosted another minor league team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-TXOK1/y-1922|title=1922 Texas-Oklahoma League (TTL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-bb10508/y-1922|title=1922 Bonham Bingers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham_Bingers|title=Bonham Bingers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==The ballparks==\nBohnam teams likely played at '''Catron Park''' and '''Simpson Park'''. Both parks still exist today as public recreational parks. Catron Park is located at the 400 block of East 3rd Street, Bonham Texas, 75418.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-292|title=Unknown in Bonham, TX history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://visitbonham.com/event/art-in-the-park-simpson-park/|title=Art in the Park @ Simpson Park}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americantowns.com/venue/catron-park-bonham-tx.html|title=Catron Park|website=www.americantowns.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cityofbonham.org/parks-and-recreation.html|title=Parks and Recreation|website=CITY OF BONHAM}}</ref>\n\nBonham built a new ballpark for the 1913 season. The name of the 1913 new ballpark is unknown.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n===[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] alumni===\n*[[Kid Nichols]] (1914, MGR) Inducted, 1949\n===Notable alumni===\n*[[Ted Blankenship]] (1921\u20131922)\n*[[Buster Chatham]] (1922)\n*[[Jim Haislip]] (1911)\n*[[Jimmie Humphries]] (1911, MGR)\n*[[Roy Leslie]] (1912\u20131913, MGR)\n*[[George Milstead]] (1921\u20131922)\n*[[Reb Russell]] (1912)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Bonham,_TX Baseball reference]\n[[Category:Fannin County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct baseball teams in Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Skilgis1900", "label": "safe", "comment": "nichols items", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonham_Boosters"}
{"title_page": "Market reduction approach", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{POV-check|date=July 2010}}\n{{essay-like|date=July 2010}}\n{{cleanup|date=July 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''Market reduction approach''' ('''MRA''') is an approach to reducing [[crime]] by reducing the opportunity for [[theft|thieves]] to [[Fence (criminal)|fence]] or resell what they have stolen.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early===\nIn 1796, the [[London]] [[magistrate]] [[Patrick Colquhoun]]<ref>Colquhoun, P. (a Magistrate) (1796) A Treatise on The Police of the Metropolis. Third edition. London. C. Dilly</ref> observed that \"[i]t rarely happens that thieves go upon the highway, or commit burglaries, until the money they have previously acquired is exhausted,\" and that \"...without a safe and ready market he [the thief] is undone.\" \n\nRecognizing the key role played by dealers in stolen goods in facilitating profit from theft and motivation for offenders to steal and with an aim to influence harsher legislation and sentencing of professional [[Fence (criminal)|fences]], the American jurisprudentialist [[Jerome Hall]]<ref>Hall, J. (1952) Theft, Law and Society. Second Edition. Indianapolis. Bobbs_Merril Co</ref> emphasised the role of the professional fence in the marketing of stolen goods and created a [[Sociopolitical typology|typology]] that distinguished between professional fences, part-time dealers, and those who knowingly buy stolen goods for their own consumption. A number of [[ethnographic|ethnography]] studies (e.g. Klockars 1974;<ref>Klockars, C. (1974) The Professional Fence. New York. Free Press</ref> Henry 1977<ref>Henry, S. (1976) Fencing With Accounts: The Language of Moral Bridging. British Journal of Law and Society. 3: 91-100</ref> and Steffensmeir 1986<ref>Steffensmeier, D. J. (1986) The Fence: In the Shadow of Two Worlds. New Jersey: Rowman and Littlefield</ref>) hinted at the influence of the market for stolen goods upon levels of theft of certain goods. \n\nA systematic study of the various ways that stolen goods are stored, sold and bought - going beyond the previous focus upon the guilty mind and level of involvement of dealers and consumers - was conducted by [[Mike Sutton (criminologist)|Mike Sutton]], who created a fivefold market typology based on his  interviews with expert prolific thieves, inexperienced thieves, fences, drug dealers and stolen goods consumers. In 1998, the UK [[Home Office]] published Sutton's report<ref>Sutton, M. (1998) Handling Stolen Goods and Theft: A Market Reduction Approach. Home Office Research Study 178. Home Office. London.\n(Peer reviewed national government research report). UK National Archives: http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110220105210/rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/hors178.pdf\n</ref> proposing a systematic framework for researching and tackling local stolen goods markets.\n\n===Modern===\nCurrent development of the market reduction approach (MRA) has its origins in a 1995 ''[[British Journal of Criminology]]'' paper: ''Supply by Theft''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bjc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pdf_extract/35/3/400 |title=SUPPLY BY THEFT: Does the Market for Second-hand Goods Play a Role in Keeping Crime Figures High? - SUTTON 35 (3): 400 - British Journal of Criminology |publisher=Bjc.oxfordjournals.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> that was followed by a 1998 [[Home Office|United Kingdom Government Home Office]] research study entitled Handling Stolen Goods and Theft: A Market Reduction Approach,<ref>http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/hors178.pdf{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> both   written by Mike Sutton<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popcenter.org/bios/sutton |title=Center for Problem-Oriented Policing &#124; Biographies |publisher=Popcenter.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621211116/http://www.popcenter.org/bios/Sutton |archive-date=2010-06-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Further work on implementing and process evaluation of the MRA was conducted by Schneider.<ref>Schneider, J. L. (2005) Stolen Goods Markets: Methods of Disposal. British Journal of Criminology. 45 (2) 129-140</ref>\n\nDescribed by Marcus Felson as \"...a simple idea in an important article\"<ref>Felson, M. (1998)Crime and Everyday Life. Second Edition. Thousand Oakes. Pine Forge Press.(see page 38).</ref> and as classic research,<ref>Felson, M. Crime and Everyday Life. Vol 4. Thousand Oakes. Sage (see Page 88)</ref> Sutton's concept of MRA has had an influence upon theory and practice regarding  stolen goods markets and markets for other illicit commodities. Some criminologists have incorporated Sutton's work on stolen goods markets to explain the issue of offenders\u2019 capacity to commit crimes.<ref>Maguire, M. Morgan, R, Reiner, R. (2007) Oxford Handbook of Criminology. Oxford. Oxford University Press. (See: page 357)</ref> The general MRA principles  have influenced work beyond research into markets for theft of high volume consumer goods, since the MRA is described as underpinning recent research into illicit markets for cultural artefacts<ref>Mackenzie, S. (2007)  Dealing in cultural objects: a new criminal law for the UK. Amicus Curiae. Issue 71.</ref><ref>Mackenzie, S. and  Green, P. (2003) Criminalising the Market in Illicit Antiquities:\nAn Evaluation of the Dealing in Cultural Objects (Offences) Act. http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1004267</ref> and as a useful method for tackling the trade in endangered species.<ref>Schneider JL. (2008) \u2018Reducing the Illicit Trade in Wildlife: The Market Reduction Approach\u2019. Journal of Contemporary Criminal Justice 24:274\u201395</ref><ref>Lemieux, A. M. and Clarke, R. V. (2009)The International Ban on Ivory Sales and its Effects on Elephant Poaching in Africa  British Journal of Criminology July 1, 2009 49: 451-471</ref>\n\nSutton's 1998 stolen goods ''Handling Report'' includes findings from the nationally representative [[British Crime Survey]] (1994). This revealed that 11 percent of those questioned had bought stolen goods in the preceding five years, and that 70 percent believed that some of their neighbours had stolen goods in their homes. The ''Handling Report'' was followed by a more comprehensive MRA policing guide to stolen goods markets.<ref>Sutton, M., Schneider, J.L. and Hetherington, (2001) Tackling theft with the market reduction approach. Home Office Crime Reduction Research Series Paper 8. (Peer reviewed national government research report) http://www.popcenter.org/problems/bicycle_theft/PDFs/Sutton_etal_2001.pdf</ref>\n\n==Application==\nKent constabulary were the first to experiment with the MRA in Operation Radium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116211827/http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |archivedate=2009-11-16 }}</ref> This experiment at systematically tackling stolen goods markets, along with another MRA initiative by the [[Greater Manchester Police]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/localgovernment/pdf/134582.pdf |accessdate=May 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606182618/http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/localgovernment/pdf/134582.pdf |archivedate=June 6, 2012 }}</ref> as routine policing (rather than merely cracking down from time to time) was independently evaluated by [[criminologists]] from The [[University of Kent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kar.kent.ac.uk/303/ |title=Implementing a Market Reduction Approach to Property Crime - Kent Academic Repository |publisher=Kar.kent.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> The evaluation found that while the MRA theory remains sound that the police forces experienced organisational difficulties implementing it correctly.\n\nBased on [[Crime Prevention#Situational Crime Prevention|Situational Crime Prevention (SCP)]] \"rational choice, opportunity reduction\" principles, and employing philosophy from [[routine activity theory]] (RAT) the MRA is designed to reduce theft through reducing the demand for stolen goods that motivated thieves to steal. In addition it seeks to make [[handling stolen goods]] at least as difficult as it is to steal them and to increase the risks of detection for all those selling and buying stolen goods. In this way the MRA answered a long-standing academic criticism that SCP and RAT did not take account of offender motivation. MRA principles are now firmly established within both SCP<ref>Clarke, R.V. ( 1999 ) Hot Products. London. Police Research paper 112. Home Office {{cite web|url=http://www.popcenter.org/problems/shoplifting/PDFs/fprs112.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813002158/http://www.popcenter.org/problems/shoplifting/PDFs/fprs112.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-13 }}</ref> RAT<ref>http://web.math.unifi.it/users/primicer/WorkshopPisa2008/Marcus%20Felson.pdf</ref> and Problem Oriented Policing (POP) key texts.<ref>http://www.popcenter.org/library/reading/pdfs/MayorsGuide.pdf</ref>\n\nThe MRA has been implemented in the United Kingdom by [[Kent Constabulary]],<ref>Joint Report from:\nKent County Council Trading Standards; Medway Council Trading Standards and Kent Police. The Kent Acts: A Case For National Legislation. (2001) Report to the Secretary of State. {{cite web|url=http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116211827/http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |archivedate=2009-11-16 }}</ref> [[West Mercia Constabulary]],<ref>Schneider, J. (2005) Stolen Goods Markets: Methods of Disposal. British Journal of Criminology. 45. 129-140 http://bjc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/azh100v1 {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120708073320/http://bjc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/azh100v1# |date=2012-07-08 }}</ref> Derby City Constabulary,<ref>Sutton, M. (2004) How Burglars and Shoplifters Sell Stolen Goods in Derby: DESCRIBING AND UNDERSTANDING THE LOCAL ILLICIT MARKETS. A Dynamics of Offending Report for Derby Community Safety Partnership. Internet Journal of Criminology.\n{{cite web|url=http://www.internetjournalofcriminology.com/Sutton%20-%20Stolen%20Goods%20in%20Derby.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713050029/http://www.internetjournalofcriminology.com/Sutton%20-%20Stolen%20Goods%20in%20Derby.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-13 }}</ref> [[Nottinghamshire Constabulary]],<ref>Nottinghamshire Constabulary South Nottinghamshire Crime & Disorder Reduction Partnership, Partnership Strategic Plan (2008 - 2011). {{cite web|url=http://www.rushcliffe.gov.uk/upload/public/attachments/258/south_notts_cdrp_partnership_strategic_plan_200811.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231163709/http://www.rushcliffe.gov.uk/upload/public/attachments/258/South_Notts_CDRP_Partnership_Strategic_Plan_200811.pdf |archivedate=2010-12-31 }}</ref> and Greater Manchester Police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/salfordadvertiser/news/s/408732_24m_boost_for_war_on_street_crime |title=\u00a32.4M boost for war on street crime &#124; Salford Advertiser |publisher=menmedia.co.uk |date=2002-08-02 |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> It is recommended crime reduction practice by the UK<ref>Burglary Toolkit: Developing Local Solutions for Local Problems. Home Office UK Publications. Acquisitive Crime Resources Library online. Burglary Toolkit: {{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/crime/acquisitive-crime-resources/burglary-toolkit?view%3DBinary |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829050145/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/crime/acquisitive-crime-resources/burglary-toolkit?view=Binary |archivedate=2012-08-29 }}</ref> United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcenter.org/learning/60steps/index.cfm?stepNum=41 |title=Crime Analysis for Problem Solvers in 60 Small Steps |publisher=Popcenter.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> and Australian governments.<ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Institute of Criminology |url=http://aic.gov.au/publications/current%20series/crm/21-40/crm032.aspx |title=Australian Institute of Criminology - The market reduction approach to reducing property crime |publisher=Aic.gov.au |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> The New Zealand Ministry of Justice conducted a review of research focused on the MRA and identified eight areas of good practice in using it to tackle property crime.<ref>New Zealand Ministry of Justice (2005). 6 Property Focused Initiatives.\nhttp://www.justice.govt.nz/publications/global-publications/r/research-on-the-effectiveness-of-police-practice-in-reducing-residential-burglary-november-2005-report-10.-overview-research-on-the-effectiveness-of-police-practice-in-reducing-residential-burglary/6-property-focused-interventions</ref>\n\nRecently, the MRA has been applied to research focused upon tackling markets for [[endangered species]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jacqueline L. Schneider |url=http://ccj.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/24/3/274 |title=Reducing the Illicit Trade in Endangered Wildlife |publisher=Ccj.sagepub.com |date=2008-05-22 |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref>\n\n==The MRA and problem oriented policing==\nIntroducing a sixth market type, e-fencing,  the MRA   is used by the [[US Department of Justice]], [[Community Oriented Policing Services|Office of Community Oriented Policing Services]], to combat crime with the [[Problem-oriented policing|problem-oriented approach to policing]].<ref>Sutton, M. (2010) Stolen Goods Markets. Problem Oriented Policing Guide No. 57. US National Institute of Justice COPS Programme. (Peer reviewed international policing guide.) http://www.popcenter.org/problems/stolen_goods/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Market Reduction Approach}}\n[[Category:Criminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{POV-check|date=July 2010}}\n{{essay-like|date=July 2010}}\n{{cleanup|date=July 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''Market reduction approach''' ('''MRA''') is an approach to reducing [[crime]] by reducing the opportunity for [[theft|thieves]] to [[Fence (criminal)|fence]] or resell what they have stolen.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early===\nIn 1796, the [[London]] [[magistrate]] [[Patrick Colquhoun]]<ref>Colquhoun, P. (a Magistrate) (1796) A Treatise on The Police of the Metropolis. Third edition. London. C. Dilly</ref> observed that \"[i]t rarely happens that thieves go upon the highway, or commit burglaries, until the money they have previously acquired is exhausted,\" and that \"...without a safe and ready market he [the thief] is undone.\" \n\nRecognizing the key role played by dealers in stolen goods in facilitating profit from theft and motivation for offenders to steal and with an aim to influence harsher legislation and sentencing of professional [[Fence (criminal)|fences]], the American jurisprudentialist [[Jerome Hall]]<ref>Hall, J. (1952) Theft, Law and Society. Second Edition. Indianapolis. Bobbs_Merril Co</ref> emphasised the role of the professional fence in the marketing of stolen goods and created a [[Sociopolitical typology|typology]] that distinguished between professional fences, part-time dealers, and those who knowingly buy stolen goods for their own consumption. A number of [[ethnographic|ethnography]] studies (e.g. Klockars 1974;<ref>Klockars, C. (1974) The Professional Fence. New York. Free Press</ref> Henry 1977<ref>Henry, S. (1976) Fencing With Accounts: The Language of Moral Bridging. British Journal of Law and Society. 3: 91-100</ref> and Steffensmeir 1986<ref>Steffensmeier, D. J. (1986) The Fence: In the Shadow of Two Worlds. New Jersey: Rowman and Littlefield</ref>) hinted at the influence of the market for stolen goods upon levels of theft of certain goods. \n\nA systematic study of the various ways that stolen goods are stored, sold and bought - going beyond the previous focus upon the guilty mind and level of involvement of dealers and consumers - was conducted by [[Mike Sutton (criminologist)|Mike Sutton]], who created a fivefold market typology based on his  interviews with expert prolific thieves, inexperienced thieves, fences, drug dealers and stolen goods consumers. In 1998, the UK [[Home Office]] published Sutton's report<ref>Sutton, M. (1998) Handling Stolen Goods and Theft: A Market Reduction Approach. Home Office Research Study 178. Home Office. London.\n(Peer reviewed national government research report). UK National Archives: http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110220105210/rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/hors178.pdf\n</ref> proposing a systematic framework for researching and tackling local stolen goods markets.\n\n===Modern===\nCurrent development of the market reduction approach (MRA) has its origins in a 1995 ''[[British Journal of Criminology]]'' paper: ''Supply by Theft''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bjc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pdf_extract/35/3/400 |title=SUPPLY BY THEFT: Does the Market for Second-hand Goods Play a Role in Keeping Crime Figures High? - SUTTON 35 (3): 400 - British Journal of Criminology |publisher=Bjc.oxfordjournals.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> that was followed by a 1998 [[Home Office|United Kingdom Government Home Office]] research study entitled Handling Stolen Goods and Theft: A Market Reduction Approach,<ref>http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/hors178.pdf{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> both   written by Mike Sutton<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popcenter.org/bios/sutton |title=Center for Problem-Oriented Policing &#124; Biographies |publisher=Popcenter.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621211116/http://www.popcenter.org/bios/Sutton |archive-date=2010-06-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Further work on implementing and process evaluation of the MRA was conducted by Schneider.<ref>Schneider, J. L. (2005) Stolen Goods Markets: Methods of Disposal. British Journal of Criminology. 45 (2) 129-140</ref>\n\nDescribed by Marcus Felson as \"...a simple idea in an important article\"<ref>Felson, M. (1998)Crime and Everyday Life. Second Edition. Thousand Oakes. Pine Forge Press.(see page 38).</ref> and as classic research,<ref>Felson, M. Crime and Everyday Life. Vol 4. Thousand Oakes. Sage (see Page 88)</ref> Sutton's concept of MRA has had a n influence upon theory and practice regarding  stolen goods markets and markets for other illicit commodities. Some criminologists have incorporated Sutton's work on stolen goods markets to explain the issue of offenders\u2019 capacity to commit crimes.<ref>Maguire, M. Morgan, R, Reiner, R. (2007) Oxford Handbook of Criminology. Oxford. Oxford University Press. (See: page 357)</ref> The general MRA principles  have influenced work beyond research into markets for theft of high volume consumer goods, since the MRA is described as underpinning recent research into illicit markets for cultural artefacts<ref>Mackenzie, S. (2007)  Dealing in cultural objects: a new criminal law for the UK. Amicus Curiae. Issue 71.</ref><ref>Mackenzie, S. and  Green, P. (2003) Criminalising the Market in Illicit Antiquities:\nAn Evaluation of the Dealing in Cultural Objects (Offences) Act. http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1004267</ref> and as a useful method for tackling the trade in endangered species.<ref>Schneider JL. (2008) \u2018Reducing the Illicit Trade in Wildlife: The Market Reduction Approach\u2019. Journal of Contemporary Criminal Justice 24:274\u201395</ref><ref>Lemieux, A. M. and Clarke, R. V. (2009)The International Ban on Ivory Sales and its Effects on Elephant Poaching in Africa  British Journal of Criminology July 1, 2009 49: 451-471</ref>\n\nSutton's 1998 stolen goods ''Handling Report'' includes findings from the nationally representative [[British Crime Survey]] (1994). This revealed that 11 percent of those questioned had bought stolen goods in the preceding five years, and that 70 percent believed that some of their neighbours had stolen goods in their homes. The ''Handling Report'' was followed by a more comprehensive MRA policing guide to stolen goods markets.<ref>Sutton, M., Schneider, J.L. and Hetherington, (2001) Tackling theft with the market reduction approach. Home Office Crime Reduction Research Series Paper 8. (Peer reviewed national government research report) http://www.popcenter.org/problems/bicycle_theft/PDFs/Sutton_etal_2001.pdf</ref>\n\n==Application==\nKent constabulary were the first to experiment with the MRA in Operation Radium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116211827/http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |archivedate=2009-11-16 }}</ref> This experiment at systematically tackling stolen goods markets, along with another MRA initiative by the [[Greater Manchester Police]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/localgovernment/pdf/134582.pdf |accessdate=May 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606182618/http://www.communities.gov.uk/documents/localgovernment/pdf/134582.pdf |archivedate=June 6, 2012 }}</ref> as routine policing (rather than merely cracking down from time to time) was independently evaluated by [[criminologists]] from The [[University of Kent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kar.kent.ac.uk/303/ |title=Implementing a Market Reduction Approach to Property Crime - Kent Academic Repository |publisher=Kar.kent.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> The evaluation found that while the MRA theory remains sound that the police forces experienced organisational difficulties implementing it correctly.\n\nBased on [[Crime Prevention#Situational Crime Prevention|Situational Crime Prevention (SCP)]] \"rational choice, opportunity reduction\" principles, and employing philosophy from [[routine activity theory]] (RAT) the MRA is designed to reduce theft through reducing the demand for stolen goods that motivated thieves to steal. In addition it seeks to make [[handling stolen goods]] at least as difficult as it is to steal them and to increase the risks of detection for all those selling and buying stolen goods. In this way the MRA answered a long-standing academic criticism that SCP and RAT did not take account of offender motivation. MRA principles are now firmly established within both SCP<ref>Clarke, R.V. ( 1999 ) Hot Products. London. Police Research paper 112. Home Office {{cite web|url=http://www.popcenter.org/problems/shoplifting/PDFs/fprs112.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813002158/http://www.popcenter.org/problems/shoplifting/PDFs/fprs112.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-13 }}</ref> RAT<ref>http://web.math.unifi.it/users/primicer/WorkshopPisa2008/Marcus%20Felson.pdf</ref> and Problem Oriented Policing (POP) key texts.<ref>http://www.popcenter.org/library/reading/pdfs/MayorsGuide.pdf</ref>\n\nThe MRA has been implemented in the United Kingdom by [[Kent Constabulary]],<ref>Joint Report from:\nKent County Council Trading Standards; Medway Council Trading Standards and Kent Police. The Kent Acts: A Case For National Legislation. (2001) Report to the Secretary of State. {{cite web|url=http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116211827/http://www.tradingstandards.gov.uk/kent/documents/KentAct%20HOreport.pdf |archivedate=2009-11-16 }}</ref> [[West Mercia Constabulary]],<ref>Schneider, J. (2005) Stolen Goods Markets: Methods of Disposal. British Journal of Criminology. 45. 129-140 http://bjc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/azh100v1 {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120708073320/http://bjc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/azh100v1# |date=2012-07-08 }}</ref> Derby City Constabulary,<ref>Sutton, M. (2004) How Burglars and Shoplifters Sell Stolen Goods in Derby: DESCRIBING AND UNDERSTANDING THE LOCAL ILLICIT MARKETS. A Dynamics of Offending Report for Derby Community Safety Partnership. Internet Journal of Criminology.\n{{cite web|url=http://www.internetjournalofcriminology.com/Sutton%20-%20Stolen%20Goods%20in%20Derby.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713050029/http://www.internetjournalofcriminology.com/Sutton%20-%20Stolen%20Goods%20in%20Derby.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-13 }}</ref> [[Nottinghamshire Constabulary]],<ref>Nottinghamshire Constabulary South Nottinghamshire Crime & Disorder Reduction Partnership, Partnership Strategic Plan (2008 - 2011). {{cite web|url=http://www.rushcliffe.gov.uk/upload/public/attachments/258/south_notts_cdrp_partnership_strategic_plan_200811.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231163709/http://www.rushcliffe.gov.uk/upload/public/attachments/258/South_Notts_CDRP_Partnership_Strategic_Plan_200811.pdf |archivedate=2010-12-31 }}</ref> and Greater Manchester Police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/salfordadvertiser/news/s/408732_24m_boost_for_war_on_street_crime |title=\u00a32.4M boost for war on street crime &#124; Salford Advertiser |publisher=menmedia.co.uk |date=2002-08-02 |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> It is recommended crime reduction practice by the UK<ref>Burglary Toolkit: Developing Local Solutions for Local Problems. Home Office UK Publications. Acquisitive Crime Resources Library online. Burglary Toolkit: {{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/crime/acquisitive-crime-resources/burglary-toolkit?view%3DBinary |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829050145/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/crime/acquisitive-crime-resources/burglary-toolkit?view=Binary |archivedate=2012-08-29 }}</ref> United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popcenter.org/learning/60steps/index.cfm?stepNum=41 |title=Crime Analysis for Problem Solvers in 60 Small Steps |publisher=Popcenter.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> and Australian governments.<ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Institute of Criminology |url=http://aic.gov.au/publications/current%20series/crm/21-40/crm032.aspx |title=Australian Institute of Criminology - The market reduction approach to reducing property crime |publisher=Aic.gov.au |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref> The New Zealand Ministry of Justice conducted a review of research focused on the MRA and identified eight areas of good practice in using it to tackle property crime.<ref>New Zealand Ministry of Justice (2005). 6 Property Focused Initiatives.\nhttp://www.justice.govt.nz/publications/global-publications/r/research-on-the-effectiveness-of-police-practice-in-reducing-residential-burglary-november-2005-report-10.-overview-research-on-the-effectiveness-of-police-practice-in-reducing-residential-burglary/6-property-focused-interventions</ref>\n\nRecently, the MRA has been applied to research focused upon tackling markets for [[endangered species]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jacqueline L. Schneider |url=http://ccj.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/24/3/274 |title=Reducing the Illicit Trade in Endangered Wildlife |publisher=Ccj.sagepub.com |date=2008-05-22 |accessdate=2012-12-26}}</ref>\n\n==The MRA and problem oriented policing==\nIntroducing a sixth market type, e-fencing,  the MRA   is used by the [[US Department of Justice]], [[Community Oriented Policing Services|Office of Community Oriented Policing Services]], to combat crime with the [[Problem-oriented policing|problem-oriented approach to policing]].<ref>Sutton, M. (2010) Stolen Goods Markets. Problem Oriented Policing Guide No. 57. US National Institute of Justice COPS Programme. (Peer reviewed international policing guide.) http://www.popcenter.org/problems/stolen_goods/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Market Reduction Approach}}\n[[Category:Criminology]]\n", "name_user": "Slip&slide9", "label": "safe", "comment": "a n to an.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_reduction_approach"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Peyton", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox saint \n|name           = [[Venerable]] <br> Patrick Peyton\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date|1909|1|9|mf=yes}}\n|death_date     = {{Death date and age|1992|6|3|1909|1|9|mf=yes}}\n|image          = Patrick_Peyton.jpg\n|imagesize      = \n|caption        = \n|birth_place    = [[Attymass]], [[County Mayo]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|death_place    = [[San Pedro, Los Angeles, California|San Pedro]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n|titles         = Priest\n|beatified_date   = \n|beatified_place  =\n|beatified_by     = \n|canonized_date   = \n|canonized_place  =\n|canonized_by     = \n|attributes       =\n|patronage        = \n|major_shrine     = \n|suppressed_date  = \n|issues           = \n|feast_day = \n|venerated_in   = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n{{infobox person|child=yes|\n|signature        = father patrick peyton signature.gif|signature_size=250px|signature_alt=Peyton's signature}}\n}}\n'''Patrick Peyton''' {{Audio|Father patrick peyton prayer appeal.ogg|Patrick Peyton}}  (January 9, 1909 \u2013 June 3, 1992), also known as \"The Rosary Priest\", was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Catholic]] [[priest]] and promoter of the [[Rosary]].\n\nPeyton is the founder of the \"[[Family Rosary Crusade]]\". He staged massive [[Rosary]] rallies in key cities of the world and extensively utilized mass communication, helped by world-recognized celebrities of [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]] at that time, promoting his ministry of binding families through prayer under the Family Rosary. Peyton was a popular and charismatic figure in [[Latin America]] and the [[Philippines]], where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and was known for his strong [[Irish people|Irish]] accent.\n\nPeyton popularized the phrases \"[[The family that prays together stays together]]\" and \"A world at prayer is a world at peace\".\n\n[[Pope Francis]] furthered Peyton towards sainthood by confirming his [[heroic virtue]] and naming him as [[Venerable]] on December 18, 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nPeyton was born Patrick Joseph Peyton in [[Attymass]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]],<ref name=chc>[http://holycrosscongregation.org/holy-ones/servant-of-god-patrick-peyton/ \"Venerable Patrick Peyton\", Congregation of Holy Cross]</ref> to subsistence-farmers John and Mary Gillard Peyton. Peyton was the sixth in a deeply religious family of four girls and five boys living in a small cottage at a 14-acre (5.66&nbsp;hectares) stony farmland near the foot of the Ox Mountains. Later on, some members of the family migrated to the United States.\n\nPeyton was sent to his mother's relatives in [[Bonniconlon]] to study at a school run by Tadhg O\u2019Leary in Bofield. As a young man, Peyton was rebellious and had moments of defying authority, resulting in dropping out of school. Despite the youthful rebellion, he remained close to his family, and deeply religious.\n\nBy his teen years, he was contemplating a vocation to become a priest. Although religious recruiters such as the [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capuchins]] and the [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|Redemptorist]] fathers visited Carracastle in search of young men wanting to pursue the priesthood, Peyton concentrated on helping his family earn a living when their father became too ill to work the farm. Some of his elder sisters were already in America and were sending remittances to help the family left in Ireland. In 1927, his sisters sent word that Patrick and his older brother Thomas could sail to the United States and join them in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. On May 13, 1928, the Peyton brothers set sail.\n\n==America==\nThe brothers arrived in [[New York City|New York]] after a 10-day trip, traveling by steerage. The two took the train from New York to [[Pennsylvania]] and lived at the home of their already married sister Beatrice, who was working as a housekeeper for [[Thomas J. Baldrige]], the state Attorney General. Peyton's sister Nellie had already spoken to [[Monsignor]] Paul Kelly of [[St. Peter's Cathedral (Scranton, Pennsylvania)|Saint Peter's Cathedral]] and mentioned Peyton's interest pursuing a [[Seminary|priestly vocation]]. Monsignor Kelly told Nellie to bring her younger brother Patrick to the cathedral as soon as he arrived. By June 1928, with hard luck in finding a job, Peyton finally met Monsignor Kelly and was offered a job of becoming the cathedral's [[Sexton (office)|sexton]]. In the words of Peyton at that time, ''a sexton was just another name for a janitor.''\n\nPeyton took the job with initial hesitation but his daily presence at the cathedral brought back the calling for a vocation and he finally decided to pursue the priesthood. Monsignor Kelly insisted that Peyton should complete his high school education prior to admission to the [[novitiate]].  He and his older brother Thomas both pursued their religious vocations while working at the cathedral. During the spring of 1929, Father Pat Dolan of the [[Congregation of Holy Cross]] came to the cathedral in Scranton in search of new seminarians. Peyton and his brother Thomas entered the minor seminary of the Congregation of Holy Cross in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]].<ref name=chc/>\n\nAfter completing their high school studies at the Holy Cross School in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]], Peyton was admitted to the Moreau Seminary within the [[University of Notre Dame]] in 1932, where he pursued [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. Peyton excelled in [[Philosophy]]. He credited Cornelius Hagerty, a professor of ethics, as the one who provided him with counseling. As a young seminarian, Peyton was attracted to become a Holy Cross Father for the order's focus towards the Holy Family and its precision towards obedience and conscience.\n\n==Marian devotion==\n[[File:Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Perez Murillo - Virgin and Child with a Rosary - WGA16360.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Peyton hosted a number of televised shows abroad promoting the [[Rosary]], where an image of [[Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Murillo]]'s painting of the [[Our Lady of the Rosary]] was always present in the background. Oil on canvas. [[Museo del Prado]].]]\n\nIn October 1938, during Peyton's second year of theology at [[Catholic University of America|Catholic University]], he was diagnosed with tuberculosis. He was transferred back to Notre Dame to the Infirmary. Father Cornelius Hagerty was influential in this stage of Peyton's life, encouraging the young seminarian to seek the help of the Blessed Virgin Mary. The doctors discovered that the patches in his lungs disappeared.<ref name=chc/>\n\nHe immediately packed his bags and left for Washington, D.C. to complete his theology studies and take his final vows. On June 15, 1941 Peyton and his brother Thomas were ordained at the [[Basilica of the Sacred Heart, Notre Dame|Basilica of the Sacred Heart]] at the University of Notre Dame as members of the Congregation of Holy Cross.<ref>[http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/the-enduring-legacy-of-now-venerable-father-patrick-peyton Pronechen, Joseph. \"The Enduring Legacy of Now-\u2018Venerable\u2019 Father Patrick Peyton\", ''National Catholic Register'', January 4, 2018]</ref>\n\n==Lifetime crusade==\n{{Main|Family Rosary Crusade|Family Theater}}\nPeyton was given very light duties following the completion of his theological studies. His first assignment was in [[Albany, New York]] as the chaplain of the [[Holy Cross Brothers]] of the Vincentian Institute. Peyton started letters to Bishops, Catholic laity, and other groups promoting the importance of families praying the Rosary as the war raged on.\n\nUtilizing radio, [[films]], [[outdoor advertising]] and later television, with the help of celebrities, artists and advertising practitioners, Peyton was one of the first pioneers of evangelism using [[mass media]]. He would also pioneer in conducting public rallies to bring families to pledge to pray the Rosary as a unit. These Rosary rallies attended by millions would become the most significant event where Peyton could be best remembered.  According to historian Hugh Wilford, \"Peyton himself was deeply conscious of the political dimension of his mission, proudly proclaiming in a 1946 radio broadcast, 'The rosary is the offensive weapon that will destroy Communism\u2014the great evil that seeks to destroy the faith'\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=GRIBBLE |first1=RICHARD  |date=2003 |title=Anti-Communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A. |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages=535\u2013558 |doi= 10.1093/jcs/45.3.535|jstor=23920511 }}</ref>\n\nThese Rosary Crusades were duplicated in different dioceses with attendees growing in numbers, taking Peyton across the globe from [[Brussels, Belgium]] to [[Madrid, Spain]] across Asia to [[Manila, Philippines]], down south of the [[equator]] to New Zealand and [[Papua New Guinea]] and into several South American cities like [[Lima, Peru]] to [[Rio de Janeiro]] in [[Brazil]]. With the help of a non-Catholic advertising practitioner, Peyton would popularize the slogan ''\"The family that prays together stays together.\"''\n\n==Death and legacy==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:father patrick peyton rosary rally philippines.gif|left|thumb|350px|Peyton shaking hands with [[Filipinos]] who gathered for the Rosary Rally in [[Archdiocese of Manila|Manila]]. 1953]] -->\n\nWith the [[Cold War]] threatening a new world peace, Peyton's work in promoting prayer, was recognized by the Holy See. His efforts earned him the title ''\"The Rosary Priest\".''\n\nControversy hounded Peyton throughout his ministry as some accused him of being a front for American intelligence during his missions in Latin America. Peyton's Rosary Crusades in Latin America were funded and, to some extent, directed by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], which was interested in combating leftist political movements in Latin America.  This came about through Peyton's connection to [[J. Peter Grace]], the great-grandson of the founder of [[W.R. Grace and Company]], a multinational corporation with interests in transport, [[sugar]], and mining in South America, whom Peyton had met in 1946 on a trans-Atlantic voyage.  Grace, who was involved with other [[CIA]] front operations as well, wrote to John Moore, the chair of the Business Advisory Council, and the two men approached [[Allen Dulles]].  Dulles later met with Grace in the White House office of Vice President [[Richard Nixon]], who expressed enthusiasm.  The CIA decided for several years where the crusades would take place, and CIA funds were expended in [[Chile]], [[Brazil]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Colombia]], until Peyton's provincial superior, Richard H. Sullivan, learned of the secret funding from [[Theodore Hesburgh]], the chair of the board of trustees of the [[University of Notre Dame]], in October 1964.  It took the [[Holy See|Vatican]] more than a year and a half to oblige Peyton to give up his CIA financing.<ref>Hugh Wilford, ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America'' [Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008], pp.&nbsp;182\u201396 .</ref> While the CIA determined the locations of the Crusades, it did not influence the content or Peyton's goal of promoting family prayer, the Rosary and devotion to the Blessed Mother.\n\nOthers accused Peyton of living an ostentatious lifestyle, living a life with Hollywood artists who volunteered their efforts in helping promote his mission. But Peyton maintained that he never solicited funds for his ministry, and the well-off were more than generous to voluntarily donate a portion of their wealth all in the name of the Blessed Mother.\n\nPeyton died peacefully on June 3, 1992, holding a rosary, in a small room at the Little Sisters of the Poor Jeanne Jugan Residence in [[San Pedro, California]]. His remains were brought to the Holy Cross Cemetery on the grounds of [[Stonehill College]] in [[Easton, Massachusetts]].\n\nBefore Peyton died, he continued to work on what was to be the last major Rosary Rally. On December 8, 1992 at the [[Rizal Park]] in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]], Manila Archbishop [[Jaime Cardinal Sin]] led the celebrations for the Golden Jubilee Celebration of the [[Family Rosary Crusade]]. Then the Archbishop of Los Angeles, [[Roger Cardinal Mahony]] was sent as [[Papal Legate]] on behalf of [[Pope John Paul II]]. Among [[Filipino people|Filipino]] Catholics, Peyton is remembered for his Sunday televised shows, where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and [[Marian devotion]] along with his famous slogan. Peyton also encouraged many businesses to start making and selling large amounts of Rosaries for distribution, which he gave freely to impoverished Filipinos living in the slums.\n\nPeyton's work continues today in his original Ministries, Family Rosary, Family Theater and Family Rosary International, and in the Father Patrick Peyton Family Institute.\n\n==Sainthood==\nCardinal [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Sean Patrick O\u2019Malley]] announced a formal declaration opening the cause for [[sainthood]] of Father Peyton on June 1, 2001, a few days after receiving approval from the Vatican's [[Congregation for the Causes of the Saints]]. The declaration paved the way for the process of determining Peyton's holiness and in the process earning the revered title of \"[[Servant of God]]\".\n\nThe [[Positio]] was sent to the C.C.S. in 2015 for assessment and theologians approved his cause on 1 June 2017. [[Pope Francis]] named him as [[Venerable]] on 18 December 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Citation\n|last=Peyton, CSC\n|first=Patrick\n|title=All For Her: An Autobiography of Father Patrick Peyton, CSC\n|publisher=Family Theater Publications, Hollywood California\n|origyear=1967|year=1996\n|asin= B0006CCAGY\n|url=http://www.christian-pages.com/si/2353.html}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Shiel\n|first=Tom\n|title=Cardinal urges Christians to twitter\n|publisher=Irish Times\n|date=April 27, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0427/1224245444798.html\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n |last        = Matilla\n |first       = Dexter R.\n |title       = 'Rosary priest' to be honored with sculpture\n |publisher   = Philippines Daily Inquirer\n |date        = March 31, 2009\n |url         = http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090430075846/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |archivedate = April 30, 2009\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Bourke\n|first=Toni\n|title=Fr Peyton remembered at 100th anniversary celebrations\n|publisher=Mayo Advertiser\n|date=April 17, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/mayo/article/11149\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Schworm\n|first=Peter\n|title=Dozens in Easton pray for canonization of the 'Rosary Priest'\n|work=Boston Globe\n|date=June 8, 2008\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2008/06/08/dozens_in_easton_pray_for_canonization_of_the_rosary_priest/\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Gribble\n|first=Richard\n|title=Anti-communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A.(Congregation of Holy Cross)\n|publisher=Journal of Church and State/J.M. Dawsons Studies on Church and State\n|date=June 22, 2003\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-829121_ITM\n}}.\n* \"Fifty Golden Years of the Family Rosary Crusade in the Philippines (1951-2001)\" written by Father [[James B. Reuter]], SJ; Gennie Q. Jota; Dean M. Bernardo, edited by Stella J. Villegas 2001 Family Rosary Crusade Foundation, Inc. \u00a9 2001\n* Wilford, Hugh. ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America''.  Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fatherpeyton.org Father Patrick Peyton, C.S.C. - Memorial Website]\n* [http://www.museumsofmayo.com/peyton1.htm Museum of Mayo]\n* [https://blog.familyrosary.org/ Family Rosary]\n* [http://www.familytheater.org Family Theater Productions]\n* [http://www.attymass.ie/peyton.htm Father Peyton Memorial Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120304053147/http://www.familyrosaryph.org/ Family Rosary Crusade - Philippines]\n\n{{canonization}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peyton, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century venerated Christians]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:American venerated Catholics]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Catholic television]]\n[[Category:Congregation of Holy Cross]]\n[[Category:Evangelists]]\n[[Category:Irish anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Irish film producers]]\n[[Category:Irish radio producers]]\n[[Category:Irish television producers]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from County Mayo]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Television evangelists]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame people]]\n[[Category:Venerated Catholics by Pope Francis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish clergy]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox saint \n|name           = [[Venerable]] <br> Patrick Peyton\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date|1909|1|9|df=no}}\n|death_date     = {{Death date and age|1992|6|3|1909|1|9|df=yes}}\n|image          = Patrick_Peyton.jpg\n|imagesize      = \n|caption        = \n|birth_place    = [[Attymass]], [[County Mayo]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|death_place    = [[San Pedro, Los Angeles, California|San Pedro]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n|titles         = Priest\n|beatified_date   = \n|beatified_place  =\n|beatified_by     = \n|canonized_date   = \n|canonized_place  =\n|canonized_by     = \n|attributes       =\n|patronage        = \n|major_shrine     = \n|suppressed_date  = \n|issues           = \n|feast_day = \n|venerated_in   = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n{{infobox person|child=yes|\n|signature        = father patrick peyton signature.gif|signature_size=250px|signature_alt=Peyton's signature}}\n}}\n'''Patrick Peyton''' {{Audio|Father patrick peyton prayer appeal.ogg|Patrick Peyton}}  (January 9, 1909 \u2013 June 3, 1992), also known as \"The Rosary Priest\", was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Catholic]] [[priest]] and promoter of the [[Rosary]].\n\nPeyton is the founder of the \"[[Family Rosary Crusade]]\". He staged massive [[Rosary]] rallies in key cities of the world and extensively utilized mass communication, helped by world-recognized celebrities of [[Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|Hollywood]] at that time, promoting his ministry of binding families through prayer under the Family Rosary. Peyton was a popular and charismatic figure in [[Latin America]] and the [[Philippines]], where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and was known for his strong [[Irish people|Irish]] accent.\n\nPeyton popularized the phrases \"[[The family that prays together stays together]]\" and \"A world at prayer is a world at peace\".\n\n[[Pope Francis]] furthered Peyton towards sainthood by confirming his [[heroic virtue]] and naming him as [[Venerable]] on 18 December 2017.\n\n==Early life==\nPeyton was born Patrick Joseph Peyton in [[Attymass]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]],<ref name=chc>[http://holycrosscongregation.org/holy-ones/servant-of-god-patrick-peyton/ \"Venerable Patrick Peyton\", Congregation of Holy Cross]</ref> to subsistence-farmers John and Mary Gillard Peyton. Peyton was the sixth in a deeply religious family of four girls and five boys living in a small cottage at a 14-acre (5.66&nbsp;hectares) stony farmland near the foot of the Ox Mountains. Later on, some members of the family migrated to the United States.\n\nPeyton was sent to his mother's relatives in [[Bonniconlon]] to study at a school run by Tadhg O\u2019Leary in Bofield. As a young man, Peyton was rebellious and had moments of defying authority, resulting in dropping out of school. Despite the youthful rebellion, he remained close to his family, and deeply religious.\n\nBy his teen years, he was contemplating a vocation to become a priest. Although religious recruiters such as the [[Order of Friars Minor Capuchin|Capuchins]] and the [[Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer|Redemptorist]] fathers visited Carracastle in search of young men wanting to pursue the priesthood, Peyton concentrated on helping his family earn a living when their father became too ill to work the farm. Some of his elder sisters were already in America and were sending remittances to help the family left in Ireland. In 1927, his sisters sent word that Patrick and his older brother Thomas could sail to the United States and join them in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. On May 13, 1928, the Peyton brothers set sail.\n\n==America==\nThe brothers arrived in [[New York City|New York]] after a 10-day trip, traveling by steerage. The two took the train from New York to [[Pennsylvania]] and lived at the home of their already married sister Beatrice, who was working as a housekeeper for [[Thomas J. Baldrige]], the state Attorney General. Peyton's sister Nellie had already spoken to [[Monsignor]] Paul Kelly of [[St. Peter's Cathedral (Scranton, Pennsylvania)|Saint Peter's Cathedral]] and mentioned Peyton's interest pursuing a [[Seminary|priestly vocation]]. Monsignor Kelly told Nellie to bring her younger brother Patrick to the cathedral as soon as he arrived. By June 1928, with hard luck in finding a job, Peyton finally met Monsignor Kelly and was offered a job of becoming the cathedral's [[Sexton (office)|sexton]]. In the words of Peyton at that time, ''a sexton was just another name for a janitor.''\n\nPeyton took the job with initial hesitation but his daily presence at the cathedral brought back the calling for a vocation and he finally decided to pursue the priesthood. Monsignor Kelly insisted that Peyton should complete his high school education prior to admission to the [[novitiate]].  He and his older brother Thomas both pursued their religious vocations while working at the cathedral. During the spring of 1929, Father Pat Dolan of the [[Congregation of Holy Cross]] came to the cathedral in Scranton in search of new seminarians. Peyton and his brother Thomas entered the minor seminary of the Congregation of Holy Cross in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]].<ref name=chc/>\n\nAfter completing their high school studies at the Holy Cross School in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]], Peyton was admitted to the Moreau Seminary within the [[University of Notre Dame]] in 1932, where he pursued [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. Peyton excelled in [[Philosophy]]. He credited Cornelius Hagerty, a professor of ethics, as the one who provided him with counseling. As a young seminarian, Peyton was attracted to become a Holy Cross Father for the order's focus towards the Holy Family and its precision towards obedience and conscience.\n\n==Marian devotion==\n[[File:Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Perez Murillo - Virgin and Child with a Rosary - WGA16360.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Peyton hosted a number of televised shows abroad promoting the [[Rosary]], where an image of [[Bartolom\u00e9 Esteban Murillo]]'s painting of the [[Our Lady of the Rosary]] was always present in the background. Oil on canvas. [[Museo del Prado]].]]\n\nIn October 1938, during Peyton's second year of theology at [[Catholic University of America|Catholic University]], he was diagnosed with tuberculosis. He was transferred back to Notre Dame to the Infirmary. Father Cornelius Hagerty was influential in this stage of Peyton's life, encouraging the young seminarian to seek the help of the Blessed Virgin Mary. The doctors discovered that the patches in his lungs disappeared.<ref name=chc/>\n\nHe immediately packed his bags and left for Washington, D.C. to complete his theology studies and take his final vows. On June 15, 1941 Peyton and his brother Thomas were ordained at the [[Basilica of the Sacred Heart, Notre Dame|Basilica of the Sacred Heart]] at the University of Notre Dame as members of the Congregation of Holy Cross.<ref>[http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/the-enduring-legacy-of-now-venerable-father-patrick-peyton Pronechen, Joseph. \"The Enduring Legacy of Now-\u2018Venerable\u2019 Father Patrick Peyton\", ''National Catholic Register'', January 4, 2018]</ref>\n\n==Lifetime crusade==\n{{Main|Family Rosary Crusade|Family Theater}}\nPeyton was given very light duties following the completion of his theological studies. His first assignment was in [[Albany, New York]] as the chaplain of the [[Holy Cross Brothers]] of the Vincentian Institute. Peyton started letters to Bishops, Catholic laity, and other groups promoting the importance of families praying the Rosary as the war raged on.\n\nUtilizing radio, [[films]], [[outdoor advertising]] and later television, with the help of celebrities, artists and advertising practitioners, Peyton was one of the first pioneers of evangelism using [[mass media]]. He would also pioneer in conducting public rallies to bring families to pledge to pray the Rosary as a unit. These Rosary rallies attended by millions would become the most significant event where Peyton could be best remembered.  According to historian Hugh Wilford, \"Peyton himself was deeply conscious of the political dimension of his mission, proudly proclaiming in a 1946 radio broadcast, 'The rosary is the offensive weapon that will destroy Communism\u2014the great evil that seeks to destroy the faith'\" <ref>{{cite journal |last1=GRIBBLE |first1=RICHARD  |date=2003 |title=Anti-Communism, Patrick Peyton, CSC and the C.I.A. |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages=535\u2013558 |doi= 10.1093/jcs/45.3.535|jstor=23920511 }}</ref>\n\nThese Rosary Crusades were duplicated in different dioceses with attendees growing in numbers, taking Peyton across the globe from [[Brussels, Belgium]] to [[Madrid, Spain]] across Asia to [[Manila, Philippines]], down south of the [[equator]] to New Zealand and [[Papua New Guinea]] and into several South American cities like [[Lima, Peru]] to [[Rio de Janeiro]] in [[Brazil]]. With the help of a non-Catholic advertising practitioner, Peyton would popularize the slogan ''\"The family that prays together stays together.\"''\n\n==Death and legacy==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:father patrick peyton rosary rally philippines.gif|left|thumb|350px|Peyton shaking hands with [[Filipinos]] who gathered for the Rosary Rally in [[Archdiocese of Manila|Manila]]. 1953]] -->\n\nWith the [[Cold War]] threatening a new world peace, Peyton's work in promoting prayer, was recognized by the Holy See. His efforts earned him the title ''\"The Rosary Priest\".''\n\nControversy hounded Peyton throughout his ministry as some accused him of being a front for American intelligence during his missions in Latin America. Peyton's Rosary Crusades in Latin America were funded and, to some extent, directed by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], which was interested in combating leftist political movements in Latin America.  This came about through Peyton's connection to [[J. Peter Grace]], the great-grandson of the founder of [[W.R. Grace and Company]], a multinational corporation with interests in transport, [[sugar]], and mining in South America, whom Peyton had met in 1946 on a trans-Atlantic voyage.  Grace, who was involved with other [[CIA]] front operations as well, wrote to John Moore, the chair of the Business Advisory Council, and the two men approached [[Allen Dulles]].  Dulles later met with Grace in the White House office of Vice President [[Richard Nixon]], who expressed enthusiasm.  The CIA decided for several years where the crusades would take place, and CIA funds were expended in [[Chile]], [[Brazil]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Colombia]], until Peyton's provincial superior, Richard H. Sullivan, learned of the secret funding from [[Theodore Hesburgh]], the chair of the board of trustees of the [[University of Notre Dame]], in October 1964.  It took the [[Holy See|Vatican]] more than a year and a half to oblige Peyton to give up his CIA financing.<ref>Hugh Wilford, ''The Mighty Wurlitzer: How the CIA Played America'' [Cambridge and London: Harvard University Press, 2008], pp.&nbsp;182\u201396 .</ref> While the CIA determined the locations of the Crusades, it did not influence the content or Peyton's goal of promoting family prayer, the Rosary and devotion to the Blessed Mother.\n\nOthers accused Peyton of living an ostentatious lifestyle, living a life with Hollywood artists who volunteered their efforts in helping promote his mission. But Peyton maintained that he never solicited funds for his ministry, and the well-off were more than generous to voluntarily donate a portion of their wealth all in the name of the Blessed Mother.\n\nPeyton died peacefully on June 3, 1992, holding a rosary, in a small room at the Little Sisters of the Poor Jeanne Jugan Residence in [[San Pedro, California]]. His remains were brought to the Holy Cross Cemetery on the grounds of [[Stonehill College]] in [[Easton, Massachusetts]].\n\nBefore Peyton died, he continued to work on what was to be the last major Rosary Rally. On December 8, 1992 at the [[Rizal Park]] in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]], Manila Archbishop [[Jaime Cardinal Sin]] led the celebrations for the Golden Jubilee Celebration of the [[Family Rosary Crusade]]. Then the Archbishop of Los Angeles, [[Roger Cardinal Mahony]] was sent as [[Papal Legate]] on behalf of [[Pope John Paul II]]. Among [[Filipino people|Filipino]] Catholics, Peyton is remembered for his Sunday televised shows, where he promoted the [[Rosary]] and [[Marian devotion]] along with his famous slogan. Peyton also encouraged many businesses to start making and selling large amounts of Rosaries for distribution, which he gave freely to impoverished Filipinos living in the slums.\n\nPeyton's work continues today in his original Ministries, Family Rosary, Family Theater and Family Rosary International, and in the Father Patrick Peyton Family Institute.\n\n==Sainthood==\nCardinal [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Sean Patrick O\u2019Malley]] announced a formal declaration opening the cause for [[sainthood]] of Father Peyton on June 1, 2001, a few days after receiving approval from the Vatican's [[Congregation for the Causes of the Saints]]. The declaration paved the way for the process of determining Peyton's holiness and in the process earning the revered title of \"[[Servant of God]]\".\n\nThe [[Positio]] was sent to the C.C.S. in 2015 for assessment and theologians approved his cause on 1 June 2017. [[Pope Francis]] named him as [[Venerable]] on 18 December 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Citation\n|last=Peyton, CSC\n|first=Patrick\n|title=All For Her: An Autobiography of Father Patrick Peyton, CSC\n|publisher=Family Theater Publications, Hollywood California\n|origyear=1967|year=1996\n|asin= B0006CCAGY\n|url=http://www.christian-pages.com/si/2353.html}}.\n* {{Citation\n|last=Shiel\n|first=Tom\n|title=Cardinal urges Christians to twitter\n|publisher=Irish Times\n|date=April 27, 2009\n|isbn=\n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0427/1224245444798.html\n}}.\n* {{Citation\n |last        = Matilla\n |first       = Dexter R.\n |title       = 'Rosary priest' to be honored with sculpture\n |publisher   = Philippines Daily Inquirer\n |date        = March 31, 2009\n |url         = http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view/20090427-201593/Rosary-priest-to-be-honored-with-sculpture\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090430075846/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifest